      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers &middot; 6 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        What Happens if a Seller Dies Before Settlement in Queensland?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The sale does not automatically collapse. The contract survives, the estate is bound, and the executor steps in. Here is how it works and what everyone involved needs to do.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The scenario is uncommon but it does happen: a seller passes away after contracts have been exchanged but before the settlement date arrives. For the buyer, and for the seller's family, this is a distressing situation on top of an already difficult time. Understanding what happens legally and practically helps everyone involved move forward with clarity rather than uncertainty.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The contract survives the seller's death</h2>
      <p>The single most important thing to understand is this: a signed contract of sale does not dissolve when a seller dies. Under Queensland property law, the contract binds the estate. The obligation to complete the sale passes from the seller personally to their estate, and the sale must proceed to settlement unless both parties agree otherwise or a court orders differently.</p>

      <p>This is not a harsh or unusual rule. It reflects the fact that a contract creates enforceable rights and obligations on both sides. The buyer has exchanged contracts in good faith, may have arranged finance, given notice to their own landlord, or committed to a purchase on the other side. The estate is bound to honour the seller's commitment.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who steps in for the seller</h2>
      <p>The person who steps into the seller's role is the executor named in the seller's will. The executor takes on the seller's obligations under the contract: they must work with the estate's solicitor to complete the conveyancing, cooperate with the buyer's solicitor on settlement, and arrange for the transfer of title from the estate to the buyer.</p>

      <p>If the seller died without a valid will (intestate), or if the named executor is unable or unwilling to act, the Supreme Court of Queensland can appoint an administrator to manage the estate. The administrator then carries out the same functions as an executor would. Either way, the sale has a legal representative who is obligated to see it through.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The probate timeline problem</h2>
      <p>Here is where the practical difficulty arises. Before an executor can deal with the deceased's property on behalf of the estate, they generally need to obtain a grant of probate from the Supreme Court of Queensland. Probate is the court's formal recognition that the will is valid and that the executor has authority to act. In Queensland, obtaining probate typically takes anywhere from several weeks to several months, depending on the complexity of the estate and how quickly the application is prepared and lodged.</p>

      <p>If the settlement date falls within that probate period, the executor cannot legally complete the transaction on time. In this situation, the executor's solicitor should notify the buyer's solicitor immediately and request an extension of the settlement date. Buyers facing this situation are generally entitled to an extension and should cooperate where reasonable. Most contracts contain provisions for extending settlement in unforeseen circumstances, and courts look dimly on buyers who refuse a reasonable extension when the delay is caused by genuine legal process outside anyone's control.</p>

      <p>If the executor expects a significant delay, it is also possible to agree on a formal variation to the contract's settlement date. Both solicitors handle this. The buyer remains contractually committed during the extension period.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the executor must do, practically</h2>
      <p>The executor's immediate tasks after the seller's death, in relation to the property sale, are:</p>
      <ul style="padding-left:1.5rem;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.75rem;">
        <li>Notify the estate's solicitor as quickly as possible so they can contact the buyer's solicitor and explain the situation.</li>
        <li>Begin the probate application promptly to minimise delays. The solicitor handles this, but the executor needs to provide the original will and cooperate with the process.</li>
        <li>Maintain the property in its contracted condition. The estate inherits the seller's obligation to deliver the property in the same state it was in at contract, so the executor should ensure the property is not damaged, neglected, or stripped of inclusions before settlement.</li>
        <li>Obtain specific tax advice regarding capital gains tax (CGT). The CGT treatment of property sold by a deceased estate is complex and depends on when the property was acquired, whether it was the main residence, and the timing of the sale relative to the date of death. An accountant or tax adviser familiar with deceased estate CGT is essential.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When the estate cannot complete the sale</h2>
      <p>In rare circumstances, the estate may genuinely be unable to proceed. Examples include where probate is contested by other beneficiaries (a will dispute), where the property is subject to a caveat or legal dispute that prevents the transfer of title, or where the estate is insolvent and the property is caught up in a broader administration process.</p>

      <p>In these cases, the contract may need to be terminated by mutual agreement between the estate and the buyer, or by court order. This is uncommon and usually involves legal proceedings. The buyer in this situation would typically be entitled to the return of their deposit and may have a claim for additional losses depending on the circumstances. Both parties need specialised legal advice immediately if the estate genuinely cannot complete.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What this means for property owners right now</h2>
      <p>Most people reading this are not facing this situation today. But there is a practical takeaway for every property owner, particularly those who own property in their own name or jointly.</p>

      <p>Ensure your will is current, names a capable executor, and that your executor knows where your property documents are. The original title document (or the details of your mortgage lender if the property is mortgaged), the signed contract if you are mid-sale, and the contact details for your solicitor should all be accessible to your executor without delay.</p>

      <p>An outdated will, an executor who cannot be contacted, or an estate that takes months to organise basic documents creates significant difficulty for a buyer who has exchanged contracts in good faith. A small amount of preparation on your part protects both your estate's obligations and your buyer's reasonable expectations.</p>

